'''Jono Carroll''' (born 12 April 1992) is an [[Irish people|Irish]] professional [[Boxing|boxer]] from [[Dublin]]. He competes at [[Super-Featherweight]].

==Professional career==
Carroll began his pro career while in [[Australia]] in 2012. He eventually returned home to Dublin where he began fighting under Paschal "Packie" Collins, out of Celtic Warrior Gym, [[Blanchardstown]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxingnewsandviews.com/2015/03/03/jono-carroll/ |publisher=Boxing News and Views |date= 3 Mar 2015 |title=Sky the limit? Exclusive interview with Prizefighter Champion Jono Carroll}}</ref> 

===Irish debut===
Carroll made his Irish professional debut in November 2014, when he faced Declan Geraghty at the [[3Arena]]. On the undercard of [[Matthew Macklin]] vs [[Jorge Sebastian Heiland]], [[Eddie Hearn]] confirmed that the winner would earn a slot at the following month's [[Prizefighter]] tournament in [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irish-boxing.com/geraghty-carroll-fighting-prizefighter-slot/|publisher=Irish Boxing |date=12 Nov 2014 |title=Geraghty and Carroll fighting for Prizefighter slot}}</ref> Carroll and Geraghty went on to produce 'Fight of the Night', in a bout which ended in the fourth round when Geraghty was disqualified for persistent use of the head, that same fight would go on to win Irish fight of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irish-boxing.com/carroll-wins-dublin-derby-fight-night-geraghty-disqualified/|publisher=Irish Boxing |date=15 Nov 2014 |title=Carroll wins Dublin derby and fight of the night as Geraghty is disqualified}}</ref> .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irish-boxing.com/carroll-geraghty-would-be-a-leap-back-he-doesnt-want-the-rematch-anyway/|publisher=Irish Boxing |date=24 Mar 2015 |title=Carroll: Geraghty would be a leap back- he doesn’t want the rematch anyway}}</ref>

===Prizefighter champion===
Carroll really stepped into the limelight when he accepted the invitation and became [[Prizefighter series|Prizefighter]] champion in December. The Dubliner was a relative unknown to British audiences when he defied the odds to defeat [[Stephen Foster (boxer)|Stephen Foster]], [[Gary Buckland]], and Michael Devine to take the [[Lightweight]] title. Carroll received high acclaim for his performances and subsequently signed a promotional deal with Eddie Hearn and [[Matchroom Sport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12040/9700756/matchroom-sign-prizefighter-winner-jono-carroll-and-welterweight-prospect-jeff-saunders |publisher=Sky Sports |date= 5 Feb 2015 |title=Matchroom sign Prizefighter winner Jono Carroll and welterweight prospect Jeff Saunders}}</ref>

===Following Prizefighter===
Despite being booked to appear on the undercard of teammate Spike O'Sullivan vs [[Chris Eubank, Jr.|Chris Eubank Jr]], Carroll accepted a different fight at just a week's notice. On the [[Wladimir Klitschko vs. Tyson Fury]] card in [[Düsseldorf]], Carroll agreed to the longest bout of his career so far - ten rounds with Miguel Gonzalez. Despite the timing, Carroll outclassed the Honduran from start to finish, winning every round on the way to a Unanimous Decision victory. "I just went out there and enjoyed myself," he told [[Sky Sports]] Box Office afterwards. "Because I never fought 10 rounds, I wanted to see what it was all about. I wanted to get through without any injuries. I'm pretty proud of that."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10083474/klitschko-vs-fury-jono-carroll-beat-miguel-gonzalez-over-10-rounds |publisher=Sky Sports |date= 28 November 2015 |title=Klitschko vs Fury: Jono Carroll beats Miguel Gonzalez over 10 rounds}}</ref>

