{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default--> | synonym = '''Céstan–Chenais syndrome''' , '''upper dorsal pontine syndrome''', | image = Circle of Willis en.svg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Basillar artery runs down the middle(in above image) and blockage is cause of this condition | pronounce = | specialty = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Raymond Céstan syndrome''' is caused by blockage of the long circumferential branches of the [[basilar artery]].<ref>http://www.clineu-journal.com/article/S0303-8467(07)00181-3/abstract</ref> It was described by [[Étienne Jacques Marie Raymond Céstan]] and [[Louis Jean Chenais]].<ref>http://www.whonamedit.com/synd.cfm/618.html</ref> Along with other related syndromes such as [[Millard-Gubler syndrome]], [[Foville's syndrome]], and [[Weber's syndrome]], the description was instrumental in establishing important principles in brain-stem localization.<ref> {{cite journal |last1 = Silverman |first1 = IE |last2 = Liu |first2 = GT |last3 = Volpe |first3 = NJ |last4 = Galetta |first4 = SL |title = The crossed paralyses. The original brain-stem syndromes of Millard-Gubler, Foville, Weber, and Raymond-Cestan |series = Archives of Neurology |date=June 1995 |pmid=7763214 |volume=52 |issue=6 |pages=635–8 |doi=10.1001/archneur.1995.00540300117021
}} </ref>
==Clinical features== * Ipsilateral [[ataxia]] and coarse [[intention tremor]] (damage to superior and middle [[cerebellar peduncle]]) * Ipsilateral [[paralysis]] of [[muscle]]s of [[mastication]] and sensory loss in face (damage to sensory and motor nuclei and tracts of [[Trigeminal nerve|CN V]]) * Contralateral loss of sensory modalities in the body (damage to [[spinothalamic tract]] and [[medial lemniscus]]) * Contralateral [[hemiparesis]] of face and body (damage to [[Pyramidal tracts#Corticospinal tract|corticospinal tract]]) may occur with ventral extension of lesion * [[Horizontal gaze palsy]] may occur (as in lower dorsal pontine syndrome)
